#: ../../G/Godwins-Law.rst:5
msgid "Godwin's Law"
msgstr "Godwin's Law"

#: ../../G/Godwins-Law.rst:7
msgid "prov\\."
msgstr "ことわざ"

#: ../../G/Godwins-Law.rst:9
msgid ""
"[Usenet] \"As a Usenet discussion grows longer, the probability of a "
"comparison involving Nazis or Hitler approaches one.\" There is a tradition "
"in many groups that, once this occurs, that thread is over, and whoever "
"mentioned the Nazis has automatically lost whatever argument was in "
"progress. Godwin's Law thus practically guarantees the existence of an upper"
" bound on thread length in those groups. However there is also a widely- "
"recognized codicil that any *intentional* triggering of Godwin's Law in "
"order to invoke its thread-ending effects will be unsuccessful. Godwin "
"himself has `discussed the subject "
"<http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/2.10/godwin.if_pr.html>`_. See also "
":ref:`Formosas-Law`\\."
msgstr ""
"[Usenet] "
"「Usenetの議論が長くなるにつれ、ナチスやヒトラーを引き合いに出す比較が現れる確率は1に近づく。」多くのグループには、これが起きるとそのスレッドは終わりで、ナチスに言及した者は進行中のいかなる議論でも自動的に負けたことになる、という伝統がある。こうしてGodwin's"
" Lawは、それらのグループでスレッドの長さに上限が存在することを事実上保証する。しかし、スレッドを終わらせる効果を狙ってGodwin's Lawを\\"
" *意図的に*\\ 引き起こそうとしても成功しない、という広く認められた付則も存在する。Godwin自身がこの話題について `論じている "
"<http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/2.10/godwin.if_pr.html>`_ 。\\ "
":ref:`Formosas-Law`\\ も参照。"
